# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: common-external-power-supply
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] The first commercial cellular network was launched by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in Japan in 1979, initially covering Tokyo.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] Within five years it expanded nationwide and became the world’s first full-scale cellular system.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] Earlier, Bell Laboratories tested a network around Chicago in 1978.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] The Nordic countries jointly developed the Nordic Mobile Telephone (NMT) standard, first deployed in Sweden in 1981.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] NMT introduced international roaming, a feature later adopted by other systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] In 1983, Ameritech launched the first 1G network in the United States using the Advanced Mobile Phone System (AMPS) and the Motorola DynaTAC handset.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] By the mid-1980s, 1G networks operated across most of Europe, Asia, and the Middle East.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] Adoption varied: Western Europe and North America expanded rapidly, while Eastern Europe and parts of Africa adopted the technology later due to economic and political limits.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] 1G introduced the cellular network concept which divided service areas into cells, each served by a low-power transmitter, which enabled frequency reuse and higher capacity.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] Although some parts of the network backbone used digital signaling, voice transmission between handset and base station remained analog, typically using frequency modulation similar to land mobile radio systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] By the early 1990s, analog 1G systems were replaced by digital GSM and cdmaOne networks, which offered higher capacity, encryption, and text messaging.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] Most 1G networks were decommissioned by the early 2000s, though some persisted longer in remote or developing regions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/1g] The last known operational 1G service, in Russia, closed in 2017.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] The most common 2G technology has been the GSM standard, which became the first globally adopted framework for mobile communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Other 2G technologies include cdmaOne and the now-discontinued Digital AMPS (D-AMPS/TDMA), as well as the Personal Digital Cellular (PDC) and Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) in Japan.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] The transition to digital technology enabled the implementation of encryption for voice calls and data transmission, significantly improving the security of mobile communications while also increasing capacity and efficiency compared to earlier analog systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2G networks were primarily designed to support voice calls and Short Message Service (SMS), with later advancements such as General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) enabling always-on packet data services, including email and limited internet access.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2G was succeeded by 3G technology, which provided higher data transfer rates and expanded mobile internet capabilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] In 1990, AT&T Bell Labs engineers Jesse Russell, Farhad Barzegar and Can A.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Eryaman filed a patent for a digital mobile phone that supports the transmission of digital data.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Their patent was cited several years later by Nokia and Motorola when they were developing 2G digital mobile phones.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2G was first commercially launched in 1991 by Radiolinja (now part of Elisa Oyj) in Finland in the form of GSM, which was defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] The Telecommunications Industry Association (TIA) defined the cdmaOne (IS-95) 2G standard, with an eight to tenfold increase in voice call capacity compared to analog AMPS.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] The first deployment of cdmaOne was in 1995.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] In North America, Digital AMPS (IS-54 and IS-136) and cdmaOne (IS-95) were dominant, but GSM was also used.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Later 2G releases in the GSM space, often referred to as 2.5G and 2.75G, include General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) and Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] GPRS allows 2G networks to achieve a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 40 kbit/s (5 kB/s).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] EDGE increases this capacity, providing a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 384 kbit/s (48 kB/s).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2.5G ("second-and-a-half generation") refers to 2G systems that incorporate a packet-switched domain alongside the existing circuit-switched domain, most commonly implemented through General Packet Radio Service (GPRS).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] GPRS enables packet-based data transmission by dynamically allocating multiple timeslots to users, improving network efficiency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] However, this does not inherently provide higher speeds, as similar techniques, such as timeslot bundling, are also employed in circuit-switched data services like High-Speed Circuit-Switched Data (HSCSD).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Within GPRS-enabled 2G systems, the theoretical maximum transfer rate is 40 kbit/s (5 kB/s).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2.75G refers to the evolution of GPRS networks into EDGE (Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution) networks, achieved through the introduction of 8PSK (8 Phase Shift Keying) encoding.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] While the symbol rate remained constant at 270.833 samples per second, the use of 8PSK allowed each symbol to carry three bits instead of one, significantly increasing data transmission efficiency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE), also known as Enhanced GPRS (EGPRS) or IMT Single Carrier (IMT-SC), is a backward-compatible digital mobile phone technology built as an extension to standard GSM.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] First deployed in 2003 by AT&T in the United States, EDGE offers a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 384 kbit/s (48 kB/s).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Evolved EDGE (also known as EDGE Evolution or 2.875G) is an enhancement of the EDGE mobile technology that was introduced as a late-stage upgrade to 2G networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] While EDGE was first deployed in the early 2000s as part of GSM networks, Evolved EDGE was launched much later, coinciding with the widespread adoption of 3G technologies such as HSPA and just before the emergence of 4G networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] This timing limited its practical application.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Evolved EDGE increased data throughput and reduced latencies (down to 80 ms) by utilizing improved modulation techniques, dual carrier support, dual antennas, and turbo codes.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] It achieved peak data rates of up to 1 Mbit/s, significantly enhancing network efficiency for operators that had not yet transitioned to 3G or 4G infrastructures.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] However, despite its technical improvements, Evolved EDGE was never widely deployed.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] By the time it became available, most network operators were focused on implementing more advanced technologies like UMTS and LTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] As of 2016, no commercial networks were reported to support Evolved EDGE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] 2G, understood as GSM and CdmaOne, has been superseded by newer technologies such as 3G (UMTS / CDMA2000), 4G (LTE / WiMAX) and 5G (5G NR).
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] However, 2G networks were still available as of 2023 in most parts of the world, while notably excluding the majority of carriers in North America, East Asia, and Australia.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Many modern LTE-enabled devices have the ability to fall back to 2G for phone calls, necessary especially in rural areas where later generations have not yet been implemented.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] In some places, its successor 3G is being shut down rather than 2G – Vodafone previously announced that it had switched off 3G across Europe in 2020 but still retains 2G as a fallback service.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] In the US T-Mobile shut down their 3G services while retaining their 2G GSM network.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Various carriers have made announcements that 2G technology in the United States, Japan, Australia, and other countries are in the process of being shut down, or have already shut down 2G services so that carriers can re-use the frequencies for newer technologies (e.g.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] As a legacy protocol, 2G connectivity is considered insecure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Specifically, there exist well known methods to attack weaknesses in GSM since 2009 with practical use in crime.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Attack routes on 2G CdmaOne were found later and remain less publicized.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Android 12 and later provide a network setting to disable 2G connectivity for the device. iOS 16 and later can disable 2G connectivity by enabling Lockdown Mode.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] In some parts of the world, including the United Kingdom, 2G remains widely used for older feature phones and for internet of things (IoT) devices such as smart meters, eCall systems and vehicle trackers to avoid the high patent licensing cost of newer technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/2g] Terminating 2G services could leave vulnerable people who rely on 2G infrastructure unable to communicate even with emergency contacts, causing harm and possibly deaths.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 3G mobile telephony was relatively slow to be adopted globally.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In some instances, 3G networks do not use the same radio frequencies as 2G so mobile operators must build entirely new networks and license entirely new frequencies, especially so to achieve high data transmission rates.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Other delays were due to the expenses of upgrading transmission hardware, especially for UMTS, whose deployment required the replacement of most broadcast towers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Due to these issues and difficulties with deployment, many carriers delayed acquisition of these updated capabilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In December 2007, 190 3G networks were operating in 40 countries and 154 HSDPA networks were operating in 71 countries, according to the Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Asia, Europe, Canada and the US, telecommunication companies use W-CDMA technology with the support of around 100 terminal designs to operate 3G mobile networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Roll-out of 3G networks was delayed in some countries by the enormous costs of additional spectrum licensing fees.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] (See Telecoms crash.) The license fees in some European countries were particularly high, bolstered by government auctions of a limited number of licenses and sealed bid auctions, and initial excitement over 3G's potential.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The 3G standard is perhaps well known because of a massive expansion of the mobile communications market post-2G and advances of the consumer mobile phone.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] An especially notable development during this time is the smartphone (for example, the iPhone, and the Android family), combining the abilities of a PDA with a mobile phone, leading to widespread demand for mobile internet connectivity.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 3G has also introduced the term "mobile broadband" because its speed and capability make it a viable alternative for internet browsing, and USB Modems connecting to 3G networks are becoming increasingly common.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The first African use of 3G technology was a 3G video call made in Johannesburg on the Vodacom network in November 2004.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The first commercial launch was by Emtel-ltd in Mauritius in 2004.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In late March 2006, a 3G service was provided by the new company Wana in Morocco.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In May 2007, Safaricom launched 3G services in Kenya while later that year Vodacom Tanzania also started providing services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In February 2012 Bharti Airtel Launched a 3.75G Network in selected cities in Kenya with a countrywide rollout planned for later in the year.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Egypt, Mobinil launched the service in 2008 and in Somaliland, Telesom started first 3G services on 3 July 2011, to both prepaid and postpaid subscription customers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Telecommunication networks in Nigeria like Globacom, Etisalat, Airtel and MTN provide 3G services to their numerous customers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Asia is also using 3G services very well.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] A lot of companies like Dialog Axiata PLC Sri Lanka (First to serve 3G Service in South Asia in 2006), BSNL, WorldCall, PTCL, Mobilink, Zong, Ufone, Telenor PK, Maxis, Vodafone, Airtel, Idea Cellular, Aircel, Tata DoCoMo and Reliance have released their 3G services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Sri Lanka's All Mobile Networks(Dialog, Mobitel, Etisalat, Hutch, Airtel,) And CDMA Network Providers (Lankabell, Dialog, Suntel, SLT) Launched 3G Services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Dialog, Mobitel launched 4G LTE Services In Sri Lanka.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Not Only (Dialog CDMA, Lankabell CDMA Have 4G LTE Services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Sri Lanka Telecom Have 4G LTE, FTTX Services..
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Nepal was one of the first countries in southern Asia to launch 3G services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Nepal's first 3G company was NTC Archived 2015-01-18 at the Wayback Machine (Nepal Telecom Corporation) and the second was Ncell.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Ncell also covered Mount Everest with 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] NTC provides high speed video calling with other 3G services, as well as post-paid and pre-paid 3G SIM cards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 3G and 4G was simultaneously launched in Pakistan on April 23, 2014, through a SMRA Auction.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Three out of five Companies got a 3G licence i.e.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Ufone, Mobilink and Telenor while China Mobile's Zong got 3G as well as a 4G licence.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Whereas the fifth company, Warid Pakistan did not participate in the auction procedure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] However, they launched 4G LTE services on their existing 2G 1800 MHz spectrum due to Technology neutral terms and became world's first Telecom Company to transform directly from 2G to 4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] With that Pakistan joined the 3G and 4G world.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In the non-mobile sector, Pakistan's biggest telecommunication company PTCL launched its 3G network, EVO, in mid-2008 and has since then established itself in this sector.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It provides 3G services in 105 cities across Pakistan.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Omantel's WorldCall also provides 3G services in 50 cities Pakistan-wide.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] They provide mobile broadband service via dongles and modems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] On 14 August 2010, Pakistan became the first country in the world to experience EVDO's RevB 3G technology that offers maximum speeds of 9.3 Mbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] At present the services of EVO Nitro (brand name) are available in Islamabad, Rawalpindi, Lahore and Karachi.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The RevA network, with speeds if up to 3.1 Mbit/s is available in over 100 cities of the country.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] State-run mobile operator Teletalk Bangladesh limited and other GSM operators GrameenPhone, Banglalink, Robi and Airtel already started hi-speed 3G+ and 3.5G services using UMTS with HSDPA facilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Grameenphone has a plan to launch 4G LTE services first time in Bangladesh using TD-LTE technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Currently Grameenphone owned 10 MHz spectrum at 3G auction by BTRC.Robi and Airtel recently merged, newly merged company has a plan to introduce 4G operation soon.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Two other data operators, Qubee and Banglalion, currently offer 4G Wimax services in Bangladesh.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] CityCell now switched off their operation by government order.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 4G LTE services have already begun in Bangladesh through all mobile operators except Teletalk, the state run mobile operator.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Bangladesh has a plan to introduce super speed 5G service soon.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] A test run will be conducted in the country in mid July 2018.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] China announced in May 2008, that the telecoms sector was re-organized and three 3G networks would be allocated so that the largest mobile operator, China Mobile, would retain its GSM customer base.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] China Unicom would retain its GSM customer base but relinquish its CDMA2000 customer base, and launch 3G on the globally leading W-CDMA (UMTS) standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The CDMA2000 customers of China Unicom would go to China Telecom, which would then launch 3G on the CDMA2000 1x EV-DO standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] This meant that China would have all three main cellular technology 3G standards in commercial use.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Finally in January 2009, Ministry of industry and Information Technology of China awarded licenses of all three standards: TD-SCDMA to China Mobile, W-CDMA to China Unicom and CDMA2000 to China Telecom.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The launch of 3G occurred on 1 October 2009, to coincide with the 60th Anniversary of the Founding of the People's Republic of China.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] By August 2011, China Telecom's 3G subscriber has exceeded 23 million .
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] On 11 December 2008, India entered the 3G arena with the launch of 3G enabled Mobile and Data services by Government owned Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Ltd MTNL in Delhi and later in Mumbai.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] MTNL becomes the first 3G Mobile service provider in India.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] After MTNL, another state operator Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] (BSNL) launched 3G services on 22 Feb 2009 in Chennai and Kolkata and later launched 3G as Nationwide.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The auction of 3G wireless spectrum was announced in April 2010 and 3G Spectrum allocated to all private operators on 1 September 2010.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] While 3G was embraced by several countries at the beginning of the millennium, it was introduced to India somewhat later.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The first network to make mobile internet browsing hassle-free was 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Even though it is sluggish those days, it is still sufficient for watching films and streaming music.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] However, telecommunications companies like Airtel have begun to shut down 3G networks in a number of Indian regions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] North Korea has had a 3G network since 2008, which is called Koryolink, a joint venture between Egyptian company Orascom Telecom Holding and the state-owned Korea Post and Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It is North Korea's only 3G Mobile operator, and one of only two mobile companies in the country.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] According to Orascom quoted in BusinessWeek, the company had 125,661 subscribers in May 2010.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The Egyptian company owns 75 percent of Koryolink, and is known to invest in infrastructure for mobile technology in developing nations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It covers Pyongyang, and five additional cities and eight highways and railways.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Its only competitor, SunNet, uses GSM technology and suffers from poor call quality and disconnections.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Phone numbers on the network are prefixed with +850 (0)192.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 3G services were made available in the Philippines in December 2008.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 3G services were made available in Singapore in October 2007.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Widespread adoption of 3G began in January 2009, with the upgrading of phones to iPhone 3G and Android.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Europe, mass market commercial 3G services were introduced starting in March 2003 by O2 in the UK and Italy.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] The European Union Council suggested that the 3G operators should cover 80% of the European national populations by the end of 2005.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Canada, Bell Mobility, SaskTel and Telus launched a 3G EVDO network in 2005.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Rogers Wireless was the first to implement UMTS technology, with HSDPA services in eastern Canada in late 2006.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Realizing they would miss out on roaming revenue from the 2010 Winter Olympics, Bell and Telus formed a joint venture and rolled out a shared HSDPA network using Nokia Siemens technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] After the AWS spectrum in 2008, new entrants to the Canadian wireless markets including but not limited to Mobilicity, Wind Mobile and Vidéotron have deployed their own UMTS networks in Canada using the AWS spectrum.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Iran Rightel won the bid for the third Operator license.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Rightel is the first 3G operator in Iran.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Rightel has commercially launched in the last months of 2011.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Jordan, Orange is the first mobile 3G operator.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Mobitel Iraq is the first mobile 3G operator in Iraq.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It was launched commercially in February 2007.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] MTN Syria is the first mobile 3G operator in Syria.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It was launched commercially in May 2010.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Lebanon Ministry of Telecoms launched a test period on September 20, 2011, where 4,000 smart-phone users were selected to enjoy 3G for one month and provide feedback.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Currently, the test period is over, MTC Touch and Alfa began rolling out the new 3G services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Saudi Arabia has got 4G as well as 3G/HSPA With Zain KSA, Saudi Telecom, and Mobily KSA.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In Trinidad and Tobago, Digicel was the first to implement UMTS services with the introduction of HSPA+ in May 2012. bmobile launched their 3G UMTS network in November 2012 with the implementation of HSPA+.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Turkcell, Avea and Vodafone launched their 3G networks commercially on 30 July 2009 at the same time.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Turkcell and Vodafone launched their 3G service on all provincial centres.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Avea launched it on 16 provincial centres.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] It was after Turkey's monopoly mobile operator Turkcell accepted number portability, mobile operators attended frequency band auction and frequencies for 3G usage distributed around mobile operators.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Turkcell got A band, Vodafone B and Avea C.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] Currently Turkcell and Vodafone have 3G networks on most of crowded cities and towns.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] In late 2005, Vodafone NZ launched their 3G network, followed by Spark NZ's XT network in 2008, and newcomer 2degrees using a combination of Vodafone's 3G towers and their own in 2009.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] 2degrees has since built more towers, and is now self-sufficient in the major cities (Auckland, Hamilton, Wellington, Christchurch and Dunedin) but relies on a roaming agreement with Vodafone to cover the rest of the country.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g-adoption] This gives it essentially the same footprint as Vodafone.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] While 2G networks such as GPRS and EDGE supported limited data services, 3G introduced significantly higher-speed mobile internet and enhanced multimedia capabilities, in addition to improved voice quality.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] It provided moderate internet speeds suitable for general web browsing and multimedia content including video calling and mobile TV, supporting services that provide an information transfer rate of at least 144 kbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Later 3G releases, often referred to as 3.5G (HSPA) and 3.75G (HSPA+) as well as EV-DO, introduced important improvements, enabling 3G networks to offer mobile broadband access with speeds ranging from several Mbit/s up to 42 Mbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] These updates improved the reliability and speed of internet browsing, video streaming, and online gaming, enhancing the overall user experience for smartphones and mobile modems in comparison to earlier 3G technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G was later succeeded by 4G technology, which provided even higher data transfer rates and introduced advancements in network performance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] A new generation of cellular standards has emerged roughly every decade since the introduction of 1G systems in 1979.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Each generation is defined by the introduction of new frequency bands, higher data rates, and transmission technologies that are not backward-compatible due to the need for significant changes in network architecture and infrastructure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Several telecommunications companies marketed wireless mobile Internet services as *3G*, indicating that the advertised service was provided over a 3G wireless network.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, 3G services have largely been supplanted in marketing by 4G and 5G services in most areas of the world.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Services advertised as 3G are required to meet IMT-2000 technical standards, including standards for reliability and speed (data transfer rates).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] To meet the IMT-2000 standards, Third-generation mobile networks, or 3G, must maintain minimum consistent Internet speeds of 144 Kbps.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, many services advertised as 3G provide higher speed than the minimum technical requirements for a 3G service.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Subsequent 3G releases, denoted 3.5G and 3.75G, provided mobile broadband access of several Mbit/s for smartphones and mobile modems in laptop computers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The 3G systems and radio interfaces are based on spread spectrum radio transmission technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] While the GSM EDGE standard ("2.9G"), DECT cordless phones and Mobile WiMAX standards formally also fulfill the IMT-2000 requirements and are approved as 3G standards by ITU, these are typically not branded as 3G and are based on completely different technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] While DECT cordless phones and Mobile WiMAX standards formally also fulfill the IMT-2000 requirements, they are not usually considered due to their rarity and unsuitability for usage with mobile phones.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The 3G (UMTS and CDMA2000) research and development projects started in 1992.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In 1999, ITU approved five radio interfaces for IMT-2000 as a part of the ITU-R M.1457 Recommendation; WiMAX was added in 2007.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] There are evolutionary standards (EDGE and CDMA) that are backward-compatible extensions to pre-existing 2G networks as well as revolutionary standards that require all-new network hardware and frequency allocations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The cell phones use UMTS in combination with 2G GSM standards and bandwidths, but *do not support EDGE*.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The latter group is the UMTS family, which consists of standards developed for IMT-2000, as well as the independently developed standards DECT and WiMAX, which were included because they fit the IMT-2000 definition.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] While EDGE fulfills the 3G specifications, most GSM/UMTS phones report EDGE ("2.75G") and UMTS ("3G") functionality.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G technology was the result of research and development work carried out by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the early 1980s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G specifications and standards were developed in fifteen years.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The technical specifications were made available to the public under the name IMT-2000.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The communication spectrum between 400 MHz to 3 GHz was allocated for 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Both the government and communication companies approved the 3G standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first pre-commercial 3G network was launched by NTT DoCoMo in Japan in 1998, branded as FOMA.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] It was first available in May 2001 as a pre-release (test) of W-CDMA technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first commercial launch of 3G was also by NTT DoCoMo in Japan on 1 October 2001, although it was initially somewhat limited in scope; broader availability of the system was delayed by apparent concerns over its reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first network to go commercially live was by SK Telecom in South Korea on the CDMA-based 1xEV-DO technology in January 2002.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] By May 2002, the second South Korean 3G network was by KT on EV-DO and thus the South Koreans were the first to see competition among 3G operators.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first commercial United States 3G network was by Monet Mobile Networks, on CDMA2000 1x EV-DO technology, but the network provider later shut down operations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The second 3G network operator in the US was Verizon Wireless in July 2002, also on CDMA2000 1x EV-DO.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] AT&T Mobility was also a true 3G UMTS network, having completed its upgrade of the 3G network to HSUPA.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first commercial United Kingdom 3G network was started by Hutchison Telecom which was originally behind Orange S.A.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In 2003, it announced first commercial third generation or 3G mobile phone network in the UK.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first pre-commercial demonstration network in the southern hemisphere was built in Adelaide, South Australia, by m.Net Corporation in February 2002 using UMTS on 2100 MHz.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] This was a demonstration network for the 2002 IT World Congress.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The first commercial 3G network was launched by Hutchison Telecommunications branded as *Three* or "3" in June 2003.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In India, on 11 December 2008, the first 3G mobile and internet services were launched by a state-owned company, Mahanagar Telecom Nigam Limited (MTNL), within the metropolitan cities of Delhi and Mumbai.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] After MTNL, another state-owned company, Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited (BSNL), began deploying the 3G networks country-wide.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Emtel launched the first 3G network in Africa.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Japan was one of the first countries to adopt 3G, the reason being the process of 3G spectrum allocation, which in Japan was awarded without much upfront cost.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The frequency spectrum was allocated in the US and Europe based on auctioning, thereby requiring a huge initial investment for any company wishing to provide 3G services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] European companies collectively paid over 100 billion dollars in their spectrum auctions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Nepal Telecom adopted 3G Service for the first time in southern Asia.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, its 3G was relatively slow to be adopted in Nepal.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In some instances, 3G networks do not use the same radio frequencies as 2G, so mobile operators must build entirely new networks and license entirely new frequencies, especially to achieve high data transmission rates.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Other countries' delays were due to the expenses of upgrading transmission hardware, especially for UMTS, whose deployment required the replacement of most broadcast towers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Due to these issues and difficulties with deployment, many carriers could not or delayed the acquisition of these updated capabilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In Asia, Europe, Canada, and the US, telecommunication companies use W-CDMA technology with the support of around 100 terminal designs to operate 3G mobile networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The roll-out of 3G networks was delayed by the enormous costs of additional spectrum licensing fees in some countries.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The license fees in some European countries were particularly high, bolstered by government auctions of a limited number of licenses and sealed bid auctions, and initial excitement over 3G's potential.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] This led to a telecoms crash that ran concurrently with similar crashes in the fibre-optic and dot.com fields.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G has also introduced the term "mobile broadband" because its speed and capability made it a viable alternative for internet browsing, and USB Modems connecting to 3G networks, and now 4G became increasingly common.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] By June 2007, the 200 millionth 3G subscriber had been connected of which 10 million were in Nepal and 8.2 million in India.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] This 200 millionth is only 6.7% of the 3 billion mobile phone subscriptions worldwide.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In Europe the leading country for 3G penetration is Italy with a third of its subscribers migrated to 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Other leading countries for 3G use include Nepal, UK, Austria, Australia and Singapore at the 32% migration level.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] According to ITU estimates, as of Q4 2012 there were 2096 million active mobile-broadband subscribers worldwide out of a total of 6835 million subscribers—this is just over 30%.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] About half the mobile-broadband subscriptions are for subscribers in developed nations, 934 million out of 1600 million total, well over 50%.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In Japan, 3G penetration was similar at about 81%, but smart phone ownership was lower at about 17%.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In China, there were 486.5 million 3G subscribers in June 2014, in a population of 1,385,566,537 (2013 UN estimate).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Since the increasing adoption of 4G networks across the globe, 3G use has been in decline.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Several operators around the world have already or are in the process of shutting down their 3G networks (see table below).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In several places, 3G is being shut down while its older predecessor 2G is being kept in operation; Vodafone UK is doing this, citing 2G's usefulness as a low-power fallback.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] EE in the UK, plans to switch off their 3G networks in early 2024.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In the US, Verizon shutdown their 3G services on 31 December 2022, T-Mobile shut down Sprint's networks on 31 March 2022 and shutdown their main networks on 1 July 2022, and AT&T has done so on 22 February 2022.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] According to Telenor IoT, 3G sunsets outpace 2G in Europe, where 19 operators in 14 countries plan to phase out 3G by 2025.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Only 8 operators in 8 nations are scheduled to shut down their 2G networks by the same year however.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Currently 3G around the world is declining in availability and support.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Technology that depends on 3G for usage are becoming inoperable in many places.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] For example, the European Union plans to ensure that member countries maintain 2G networks as a fallback, so 3G devices that are backwards compatible with 2G frequencies can continue to be used.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, in countries that plan to decommission 2G networks or have already done so as well, such as the United States and Singapore, devices supporting only 3G and backwards compatible with 2G are becoming inoperable.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] As of February 2022, less than 1% of cell phone customers in the United States used 3G; AT&T offered free replacement devices to some customers in the run-up to its shutdown.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] It has been estimated that there are almost 8,000 patents declared essential (FRAND) related to the 483 technical specifications which form the 3GPP and 3GPP2 standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Twelve companies accounted in 2004 for 90% of the patents (Qualcomm, Ericsson, Nokia, Motorola, Philips, NTT DoCoMo, Siemens, Mitsubishi, Fujitsu, Hitachi, InterDigital, and Matsushita).
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Even then, some patents essential to 3G might not have been declared by their patent holders.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] It is believed that Nortel and Lucent have undisclosed patents essential to these standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Furthermore, the existing 3G Patent Platform Partnership Patent pool has little impact on FRAND protection because it excludes the four largest patent owners for 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] ITU has not provided a clear definition of the data rate that users can expect from 3G equipment or providers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Thus users sold 3G service may not be able to point to a standard and say that the rates it specifies are not being met.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G networks offer greater security than their 2G predecessors.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] By allowing the UE (User Equipment) to authenticate the network it is attaching to, the user can be sure the network is the intended one and not an impersonator.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3G networks use the KASUMI block cipher instead of the older A5/1 stream cipher.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, a number of serious weaknesses in the KASUMI cipher have been identified.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] In addition to the 3G network infrastructure security, end-to-end security is offered when application frameworks such as IMS are accessed, although this is not strictly a 3G property.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] The bandwidth and location capabilities introduced by 3G networks enabled a wide range of applications that were previously impractical or unavailable on 2G networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Among the most significant advancements was the ability to perform data-intensive tasks, such as browsing the internet seamlessly while on the move, as well as engaging in other activities that benefited from faster data speeds and enhanced reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Beyond personal communication, 3G networks supported applications in various fields, including medical devices, fire alarms, and ankle monitors.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] This versatility marked a significant milestone in cellular communications, as 3G became the first network to enable such a broad range of use cases.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] By expanding its functionality beyond traditional mobile phone usage, 3G set the stage for the integration of cellular networks into a wide array of technologies and services, paving the way for further advancements with subsequent generations of mobile networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] Both 3GPP and 3GPP2 are working on the extensions to 3G standards that are based on an all-IP network infrastructure and using advanced wireless technologies such as MIMO.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] These specifications already display features characteristic for IMT-Advanced (4G), the successor of 3G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] However, falling short of the bandwidth requirements for 4G (which is 1 Gbit/s for stationary and 100 Mbit/s for mobile operation), these standards are classified as 3.9G or Pre-4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/3g] 3GPP plans to meet the 4G goals with LTE Advanced, whereas Qualcomm has halted UMB development in favour of the LTE family.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The earliest deployed technologies marketed as "4G" were Long-Term Evolution (LTE), developed by the 3GPP group, and Mobile Worldwide Interoperability for Microwave Access (Mobile WiMAX), based on IEEE specifications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] These provided significant enhancements over previous 3G and 2G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Since the first-release versions of Mobile WiMAX and LTE support much less than 1 Gbit/s peak bit rate, they are not fully IMT-Advanced compliant, but are often branded 4G by service providers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] According to operators, a generation of the network refers to the deployment of a new non-backward-compatible technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Both the original LTE and WiMAX standards had previously sometimes been referred to as 3.9G/3.95G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The ITU's new definition for 4G also included Evolved High Speed Packet Access (HSPA+).
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Mobile WiMAX Release 2 (also known as *WirelessMAN-Advanced* or *IEEE 802.16m*) and LTE Advanced (LTE-A) are IMT-Advanced compliant backwards compatible versions of the above two systems, standardized during the spring 2011, and promising speeds in the order of 1 Gbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In January 2012, the ITU backtracked on its previous definition for 4G, claiming that Mobile WiMAX 2 and LTE Advanced are "true 4G" while their predecessors are "transitional" 3G-4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As opposed to earlier generations, a 4G system does not support traditional circuit-switched telephony service, but instead relies on all-Internet Protocol (IP) based communication such as IP telephony.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The peak bit rate is further improved by smart antenna arrays for multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] New mobile generations have appeared about every ten years since the first move from 1981 analog (1G) to digital (2G) transmission in 1992.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This was followed, in 2001, by 3G multi-media support, spread spectrum transmission and a minimum peak bit rate of 200 kbit/s, in 2011/2012 to be followed by "real" 4G, which refers to all-IP packet-switched networks giving mobile ultra-broadband (gigabit speed) access.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] While the ITU has adopted recommendations for technologies that would be used for future global communications, they do not actually perform the standardization or development work themselves, instead relying on the work of other standard bodies such as IEEE, WiMAX Forum, and 3GPP.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In the mid-1990s, the ITU-R standardization organization released the IMT-2000 requirements as a framework for what standards should be considered 3G systems, requiring 2000 kbit/s peak bit rate.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In theory speeds up to 672 Mbit/s are possible, but have not been deployed yet.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The fastest 3G-based standard in the CDMA2000 family is the EV-DO Rev.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] B, which is available since 2010 and offers 15.67 Mbit/s downstream.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In 2008, ITU-R specified the IMT Advanced (International Mobile Telecommunications Advanced) requirements for 4G systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This article refers to 4G using IMT-Advanced (*International Mobile Telecommunications Advanced*), as defined by ITU-R.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In September 2009, the technology proposals were submitted to the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) as 4G candidates.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Implementations of Mobile WiMAX and first-release LTE were largely considered a stopgap solution that would offer a considerable boost until WiMAX 2 (based on the 802.16m specification) and LTE Advanced was deployed.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The latter's standard versions were ratified in spring 2011.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The first set of 3GPP requirements on LTE Advanced was approved in June 2008.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] LTE Advanced was standardized in 2010 as part of Release 10 of the 3GPP specification.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Some sources consider first-release LTE and Mobile WiMAX implementations as pre-4G or near-4G, as they do not fully comply with the planned requirements of 1 Gbit/s for stationary reception and 100 Mbit/s for mobile.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Confusion has been caused by some mobile carriers who have launched products advertised as 4G but which according to some sources are pre-4G versions, commonly referred to as 3.9G, which do not follow the ITU-R defined principles for 4G standards, but today can be called 4G according to ITU-R.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Vodafone Netherlands for example, advertised LTE as 4G, while advertising LTE Advanced as their '4G+' service.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] LTE Advanced (Long-Term Evolution Advanced) is a candidate for IMT-Advanced standard, formally submitted by the 3GPP organization to ITU-T in the fall 2009, and as of 2013 has been released to the public.The target of 3GPP LTE Advanced is to reach and surpass the ITU requirements.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] LTE Advanced is essentially an enhancement to LTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] It is not a new technology, but rather an improvement on the existing LTE network.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This upgrade path makes it more cost effective for vendors to offer LTE and then upgrade to LTE Advanced which is similar to the upgrade from WCDMA to HSPA.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] LTE and LTE Advanced will also make use of additional spectrums and multiplexing to allow it to achieve higher data speeds.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Coordinated Multi-point Transmission will also allow more system capacity to help handle the enhanced data speeds.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The IEEE 802.16m or WirelessMAN-Advanced (WiMAX 2) evolution of 802.16e is under development, with the objective to fulfill the IMT-Advanced criteria of 1 Gbit/s for stationary reception and 100 Mbit/s for mobile reception.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The pre-4G 3GPP Long-Term Evolution (LTE) technology is often branded "4G – LTE", but the first LTE release does not fully comply with the IMT-Advanced requirements.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] LTE has a theoretical net bit rate capacity of up to 100 Mbit/s in the downlink and 50 Mbit/s in the uplink if a 20 MHz channel is used – and more if multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO), i.e. antenna arrays, are used.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The physical radio interface was at an early stage named *High Speed OFDM Packet Access* (HSOPA), now named Evolved UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access (E-UTRA).
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The first LTE USB dongles do not support any other radio interface.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The world's first publicly available LTE service was opened in the two Scandinavian capitals, Stockholm (Ericsson and Nokia Siemens Networks systems) and Oslo (a Huawei system) on December 14, 2009, and branded 4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The user terminals were manufactured by Samsung.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As of November 2012, the five publicly available LTE services in the United States are provided by MetroPCS, Verizon Wireless, AT&T Mobility, U.S.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] T-Mobile Hungary launched a public beta test (called *friendly user test*) on 7 October 2011, and has offered commercial 4G LTE services since 1 January 2012.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In South Korea, SK Telecom and LG U+ have enabled access to LTE service since 1 July 2011 for data devices, slated to go nationwide by 2012.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] KT Telecom closed its 2G service by March 2012 and completed nationwide LTE service in the same frequency around 1.8 GHz by June 2012.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In the United Kingdom, LTE services were launched by EE in October 2012, by O2 and Vodafone in August 2013, and by Three in December 2013.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The Mobile WiMAX (IEEE 802.16e-2005) mobile wireless broadband access (MWBA) standard (also known as WiBro in South Korea) is sometimes branded 4G, and offers peak data rates of 128 Mbit/s downlink and 56 Mbit/s uplink over 20 MHz wide channels.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In June 2006, the world's first commercial mobile WiMAX service was opened by KT in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Sprint has begun using Mobile WiMAX, as of 29 September 2008, branding it as a "4G" network even though the current version does not fulfill the IMT Advanced requirements on 4G systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In Russia, Belarus and Nicaragua WiMax broadband internet access were offered by a Russian company Scartel, and was also branded 4G, Yota.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In the latest version of the standard, WiMax 2.1, the standard has been updated to be not compatible with earlier WiMax standard, and is instead interchangeable with LTE-TDD system, effectively merging WiMax standard with LTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As Long-Term Evolution (LTE) and WiMAX were adopted by the global telecommunications industry, LTE emerged as a primary 4G standard and saw significant adoption in the Chinese market.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Although TD-LTE, one of the two LTE air interface variants, was initially less mature than its FDD-LTE counterpart, various domestic and international wireless carriers eventually adopted the technology..
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] IBM's data shows that 67% of the operators are considering LTE because this is the main source of their future market.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The above news also confirms IBM's statement that while only 8% of the operators are considering the use of WiMAX, WiMAX can provide the fastest network transmission to its customers on the market and could challenge LTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] TD-LTE is not the first 4G wireless mobile broadband network data standard, but it is China's 4G standard that was amended and published by China's largest telecom operator – China Mobile.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] After a series of field trials, is expected to be released into the commercial phase in the next two years.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] UMB (Ultra Mobile Broadband) was the brand name for a discontinued 4G project within the 3GPP2 standardization group to improve the CDMA2000 mobile phone standard for next generation applications and requirements.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In November 2008, Qualcomm, UMB's lead sponsor, announced it was ending development of the technology, favoring LTE instead.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The objective was to achieve data speeds over 275 Mbit/s downstream and over 75 Mbit/s upstream.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] At an early stage the Flash-OFDM system was expected to be further developed into a 4G standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The iBurst system (or HC-SDMA, High Capacity Spatial Division Multiple Access) was at an early stage considered to be a 4G predecessor.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] It was later further developed into the Mobile Broadband Wireless Access (MBWA) system, also known as IEEE 802.20.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As opposed to earlier generations, 4G systems do not support circuit switched telephony.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] IEEE 802.20, UMB and OFDM standards lack soft-handover support, also known as cooperative relaying.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Recently, new access schemes like Orthogonal FDMA (OFDMA), Single Carrier FDMA (SC-FDMA), Interleaved FDMA, and Multi-carrier CDMA (MC-CDMA) are gaining more importance for the next generation systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] These are based on efficient FFT algorithms and frequency domain equalization, resulting in a lower number of multiplications per second.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] They also make it possible to control the bandwidth and form the spectrum in a flexible way.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] However, they require advanced dynamic channel allocation and adaptive traffic scheduling.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] WiMax is using OFDMA in the downlink and in the uplink.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] For the LTE (telecommunication), OFDMA is used for the downlink; by contrast, Single-carrier FDMA is used for the uplink since OFDMA contributes more to the PAPR related issues and results in nonlinear operation of amplifiers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] IFDMA provides less power fluctuation and thus requires energy-inefficient linear amplifiers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Similarly, MC-CDMA is in the proposal for the IEEE 802.20 standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] These access schemes offer the same efficiencies as older technologies like CDMA.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Apart from this, scalability and higher data rates can be achieved.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The other important advantage of the above-mentioned access techniques is that they require less complexity for equalization at the receiver.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This is an added advantage especially in the MIMO environments since the spatial multiplexing transmission of MIMO systems inherently require high complexity equalization at the receiver.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In addition to improvements in these multiplexing systems, improved modulation techniques are being used.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Whereas earlier standards largely used Phase-shift keying, more efficient systems such as 64QAM are being proposed for use with the 3GPP Long-Term Evolution standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Unlike 3G, which is based on two parallel infrastructures consisting of circuit switched and packet switched network nodes, 4G is based on packet switching *only*.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This requires low-latency data transmission.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As IPv4 addresses are (nearly) exhausted, IPv6 is essential to support the large number of wireless-enabled devices that communicate using IP.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] By increasing the number of IP addresses available, IPv6 removes the need for network address translation (NAT), a method of sharing a limited number of addresses among a larger group of devices, which has a number of problems and limitations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] When using IPv6, some kind of NAT is still required for communication with legacy IPv4 devices that are not also IPv6-connected.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As of June 2009, Verizon has posted specifications that require any 4G devices on its network to support IPv6.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The performance of radio communications depends on an antenna system, termed smart or intelligent antenna.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Recently, multiple antenna technologies are emerging to achieve the goal of 4G systems such as high rate, high reliability, and long range communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In the early 1990s, to cater for the growing data rate needs of data communication, many transmission schemes were proposed.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] One technology, spatial multiplexing, gained importance for its bandwidth conservation and power efficiency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Spatial multiplexing involves deploying multiple antennas at the transmitter and at the receiver.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Independent streams can then be transmitted simultaneously from all the antennas.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This technology, called MIMO (as a branch of intelligent antenna), multiplies the base data rate by (the smaller of) the number of transmit antennas or the number of receive antennas.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Apart from this, the reliability in transmitting high speed data in the fading channel can be improved by using more antennas at the transmitter or at the receiver.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This is called *transmit* or *receive diversity*.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Both transmit/receive diversity and transmit spatial multiplexing are categorized into the space-time coding techniques, which does not necessarily require the channel knowledge at the transmitter.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The other category is closed-loop multiple antenna technologies, which require channel knowledge at the transmitter.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] One of the key technologies for 4G and beyond is called Open Wireless Architecture (OWA), supporting multiple wireless air interfaces in an open architecture platform.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] SDR is one form of open wireless architecture (OWA).
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Since 4G is a collection of wireless standards, the final form of a 4G device will constitute various standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This can be efficiently realized using SDR technology, which is categorized to the area of the radio convergence.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In 1991, WiLAN founders Hatim Zaghloul and Michel Fattouche invented wideband orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (WOFDM), the basis for wideband wireless communication applications, including 4G mobile communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] The 4G system was originally envisioned by the DARPA, the US Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Since the 2.5G GPRS system, cellular systems have provided dual infrastructures: packet switched nodes for data services, and circuit switched nodes for voice calls.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In 4G systems, the circuit-switched infrastructure is abandoned and only a packet-switched network is provided, while 2.5G and 3G systems require both packet-switched and circuit-switched network nodes, i.e. two infrastructures in parallel.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] This means that in 4G traditional voice calls are replaced by IP telephony.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Since 2009, the LTE-Standard has strongly evolved over the years, resulting in many deployments by various operators across the globe.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] For an overview of commercial LTE networks and their respective historic development see: List of LTE networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Among the vast range of deployments, many operators are considering the deployment and operation of LTE networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] A compilation of planned LTE deployments can be found at: List of planned LTE networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] 4G introduces a potential inconvenience for those who travel internationally or wish to switch carriers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In order to make and receive 4G voice calls (VoLTE), the subscriber handset must not only have a matching frequency band (and in some cases require unlocking), it must also have the matching enablement settings for the local carrier and/or country.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] A major issue in 4G systems is to make the high bit rates available in a larger portion of the cell, especially to users in an exposed position in between several base stations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] In current research, this issue is addressed by macro-diversity techniques, also known as group cooperative relay, and also by Beam-Division Multiple Access (BDMA).
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Pervasive networks are an amorphous and at present entirely hypothetical concept where the user can be simultaneously connected to several wireless access technologies and can seamlessly move between them (See vertical handoff, IEEE 802.21).
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] These access technologies can be Wi-Fi, UMTS, EDGE, or any other future access technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] Included in this concept is also smart-radio (also known as cognitive radio) technology to efficiently manage spectrum use and transmission power as well as the use of mesh routing protocols to create a pervasive network.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] As of 2023, many countries and regions have started the transition from 4G to 5G, the next generation of cellular technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] 5G promises even faster speeds, lower latency, and the ability to connect a vast number of devices simultaneously.
[src:common-external-power-supply/4g] 4G networks are expected to coexist with 5G networks for several years, providing coverage in areas where 5G is not available.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Like earlier cellular systems, 5G networks divide service areas into smaller zones called cells, which are served by fixed cell sites.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Compatible devices connect by radio to local base stations, which are linked to an operator's core network and to external networks such as the Internet through backhaul connections.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G can be deployed using low-band, mid-band, and high-band radio spectrum, with coverage and performance depending heavily on the frequencies used, network design, congestion, and device capabilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Compared with 4G, 5G is designed to provide higher data rates, greater network capacity, lower latency, improved support for dense device deployments, and more flexible network management.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Actual user speeds are typically much lower than peak values and vary by operator, location, spectrum band, signal quality, and network load.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G is used for mobile broadband, fixed wireless access, private and industrial networks, and machine-type communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Its standards support features such as network slicing, edge computing, non-public networks, and ultra-reliable low-latency services, although these capabilities are not present in every deployment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The rollout of 5G has required new spectrum allocations and upgrades to radio access, transport, and core-network infrastructure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It has also raised issues involving deployment cost, energy use, vendor security, and public claims about radio-frequency health effects.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G is being deployed alongside 4G networks and is expected to coexist with them for many years.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2008, NASA and the Machine-to-Machine Intelligence Corporation (M2Mi) conducted nanosatellite communication studies that influenced early next-generation network concepts.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2012, New York University established NYU Wireless, a research center focused on millimeter-wave communication.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The same year, the University of Surrey founded the 5G Innovation Centre, funded by £35 million from public and industry partners including Huawei and Samsung.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Also in 2012, the European Union launched the *Mobile and Wireless Communications Enablers for the Twenty-Twenty Information Society (METIS)* project to align emerging network research with international standardization.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2013, the ITU-R Working Party 5D began studies on *IMT-2020*, later formalized as the 5G standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] During the same period, major firms such as Samsung Electronics, NTT Docomo, and Huawei conducted early trials.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Samsung tested a prototype achieving more than 1 Gbit/s across 2 km using 8 × 8 MIMO antennas.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] NTT Docomo received a government award at CEATEC for high-speed network development, while Huawei announced a US$600 million program to advance mobile network technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] On April 3, 2019, South Korea launched its national network, the first full commercial deployment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Hours later, Verizon began limited service in select U.S. cities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In June 2019, Globe Telecom introduced the Philippines' first next-generation network, and in December 2019, AT&T launched a consumer service in the United States that expanded nationwide during 2020.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Commercial 5G deployment expanded rapidly through 2020.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Beyond public mobile networks, it was also adopted in private industrial and enterprise systems, including operation in unlicensed spectrum (NR-U) and licensed non-public networks (NPNs).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Private 5G networks became important for Industry 4.0 automation and smart manufacturing.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Early rollouts used non-standalone (NSA) mode—with 4G cores—before networks transitioned to standalone (SA) mode with dedicated 5G cores.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] South Korea’s 2019 rollout used equipment from Samsung, Ericsson, and Nokia; LG U Plus also deployed Huawei hardware.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Samsung supplied most of the roughly 86,000 sites, while SK Telecom, KT Corporation, and LG U Plus concentrated coverage in major cities using the 3.5 GHz band under NSA operation.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Reported download speeds averaged 200–400 Mbit/s, and subscriptions grew from about 260,000 to 4.7 million during 2019.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Following these early deployments, T-Mobile US launched the first nationwide standalone network in 2020.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Ericsson projected that by the mid-2020s, 5G networks would reach about 65 percent of the global population.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Major suppliers of 5G radio and core systems included Altiostar, Cisco Systems, Datang Telecom/Fiberhome, Ericsson, Huawei, Nokia, Qualcomm, Samsung, and ZTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Huawei was estimated to hold about 70 percent of global 5G base stations by 2023.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By 2022, network speeds in many regions had stabilized, and operators began testing 5.5G upgrades to improve capacity and latency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By the early 2020s, large-scale commercial 5G networks were active across most developed markets, and rollout in developing regions was still accelerating.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Small cells are low-power radio nodes that extend network capacity in dense or indoor areas.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] They operate over short distances, typically a few dozen to a few hundred metres, and are used to maintain coverage for mmWave signals.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Massive multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems use large antenna arrays to increase capacity and spectral efficiency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] They extend conventional MIMO by serving multiple users simultaneously and steering signals toward them to reduce interference.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Beamforming directs radio energy toward specific users.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In analogue beamforming, antenna outputs are combined to focus signal power in one direction.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Digital beamforming transmits data streams across multiple layers to improve signal strength and reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Non-orthogonal multiple access assigns different power levels to users sharing the same frequency resources to improve spectral efficiency.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G NR uses polar codes for control channels and low-density parity-check codes (LDPC) for data channels, replacing the turbo codes used in 4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Research has explored the use of 5G mmWave networks for wireless power transfer.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Studies using wavelengths between 1 mm and 10 mm remain experimental.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The 5G core (5GC) is a service-oriented, software-defined system that separates control and user planes and supports flexible deployment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It replaces the 4G Evolved Packet Core with modular, software-based network functions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) enable software-based configuration, scaling, and management of networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Together with network slicing, these technologies support applications such as the Internet of things, connected vehicles, and industrial automation.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Service-based architecture (SBA) integrates SDN and NFV principles and replaces the 4G EPC framework with modular network functions that communicate through RESTful APIs.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Each function registers with a network repository function (NRF), which enables independent scaling and interoperability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Each network function performs a defined role within the 5G core, replacing or extending elements from the 4G EPC.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G networks use multiple parts of the radio spectrum.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] They operate across three main frequency ranges—low, mid, and high bands—which balance speed, coverage, and signal quality differently.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Between 2016 and 2019, regulators in many regions, including the United States and the European Union, reallocated large sections of spectrum for 5G through auctions and new licensing rules.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By 2019, more than 50 countries had assigned or planned to assign 5G frequencies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 3GPP Release 16, the standard added 5G NR-U, allowing operation in both unlicensed and licensed spectrum.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Low- and mid-band 5G provide broad coverage and reliable indoor reception.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] High-band signals weaken rapidly and may lose over 100 dB when passing through common building materials.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Operators use beamforming antennas, small cells, and signal repeaters to extend range and improve indoor coverage.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Technologies such as License Assisted Access (LAA) and LTE-WLAN Aggregation (LWA) let mobile networks share unlicensed spectrum with Wi-Fi.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Cloud-based RAN systems and dense small-cell layouts help narrow the performance gap between cellular and Wi-Fi links.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The ITU-R defines three main application areas for 5G: enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), and massive machine-type communications (mMTC).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] These categories describe the main uses of 5G: faster mobile connections (eMBB), highly reliable and responsive communication (URLLC), and large-scale links between machines (mMTC).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By 2020, eMBB was widely deployed, while URLLC and mMTC were still in development.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) provides much faster internet and higher capacity than 4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It supports intensive data use in busy areas such as city centres, stadiums, and transport hubs.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) are designed for time-critical applications such as factory automation, remote medical procedures, and traffic systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Shorter transmission delays improve precision and reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Massive machine-type communications (mMTC) connect large numbers of low-power devices such as sensors and meters.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] These networks underpin the Internet of things (IoT) by allowing machines to exchange data autonomously in industry, transport, and urban systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G is used in transport, manufacturing, and energy systems that require constant, low-latency communication.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The 5G Automotive Association develops vehicle-to-everything (C-V2X) standards that allow cars to exchange safety information with nearby vehicles and infrastructure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Drones and autonomous vehicles use 5G for navigation, remote control, and real-time data transmission.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Low-latency connections also enable digital twin models—virtual copies of machines or buildings that show real-time performance data used for monitoring and maintenance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G extends to public safety, broadband access, and media delivery.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Emergency services use it for live video, data, and reliable push-to-talk communication.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Fixed wireless access (FWA) provides home and business broadband using 5G radio links instead of wired connections, especially in rural areas where laying cables is costly.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G Broadcast trials in Europe show that local 5G networks can deliver live television and radio to many devices simultaneously without using mobile data plans.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Voice over NR (VoNR) allows phone calls to be made over 5G's internet-based network, similar to Voice over LTE (VoLTE) on 4G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G can deliver much higher data rates than 4G, up to ten times faster.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Theoretical peak download speeds reach up to 20 Gbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In practice, average 5G download speeds in the United States have been measured at about 186 Mbit/s by T-Mobile, while South Korea in 2022 led globally with averages near 430 Mbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G networks are also designed to provide much greater total capacity and efficiency than 4G, with up to a hundredfold projected increase.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The most widely deployed version, sub-6 GHz (mid-band) 5G, provides speeds of roughly 10–1000 Mbit/s with wider reach than mmWave bands.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] C-Band (n77/n78) was introduced in the U.S. in 2022, though activation by Verizon and AT&T was briefly delayed due to FAA safety concerns.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The highest 5G speed measured in a deployed network is 5.9 Gbit/s (2023).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Low-band frequencies such as n5 cover larger areas per cell but deliver lower data rates of around 5–250 Mbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Typical *air latency* for 5G is around 8–12 ms, excluding retransmissions and handovers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Verizon reported about 30 ms latency in early deployments.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Edge servers located near base stations can reduce round-trip time to roughly 14 ms and minimize jitter to about 1.8 ms.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Latency increases substantially during handovers, ranging from 50 to 150 ms depending on network conditions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Ongoing research focuses on reducing these interruptions by adjusting handover margins and time-to-trigger parameters.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G uses adaptive modulation and coding schemes (MCS) to maintain a low block error rate (BLER).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] When the error rate exceeds a threshold, the system automatically switches to a lower MCS to prioritize reliability over speed.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The range of 5G varies with transmit power, frequency, and interference.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] High-frequency mmWave bands (e.g., n258) have a shorter range than mid-band (n78), which in turn has a shorter range than low-band (n5).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Operators use network simulation and drive testing to measure the actual range and coverage of these bands, as real-world performance can differ from marketing claims.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The term 5G was first associated with the International Telecommunication Union's IMT-2020 standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It defines peak download and upload rates of 20 and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) later proposed its 5G New Radio (NR) technology for IMT-2020.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Early FR1 deployments reusing 4G infrastructure (non-standalone mode) have been reported to provide 15–50 percent higher throughput than advanced 4G networks under favorable conditions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G networks can operate in Non-Standalone (NSA) mode using existing LTE infrastructure or Standalone (SA) mode using a dedicated 5G Core (5GC) network.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Other organizations also contribute to 5G standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The DECT-2020 specification defines DECT NR+, a non-cellular, mesh-based radio system recognized by ITU as part of 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The IEEE defines standards for wired links between the remote radio unit (RRU) and the baseband unit (BBU).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5Gi was developed in India by IIT Madras, IIT Hyderabad, the Telecommunications Standards Development Society India (TSDSI) and the Centre of Excellence in Wireless Technology (CEWiT).
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It extends 5G coverage in rural and remote areas through low-mobility large-cell (LMLC) configurations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5Gi was merged in April 2022 into the global 5G NR standard in 3GPP Release 17.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In the Internet of things (IoT), 3GPP defines the evolution of NB-IoT and eMTC to support low-power wide-area applications such as connected sensors and meters.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 3GPP standards also define advanced communication services for voice and connected devices.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 3GPP defines Voice over NR as a technology that enables native, high-quality voice over a 5G Standalone network through the 5G System Architecture.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Unlike early 5G Non-Standalone deployments that relied on Evolved Packet System Fallback, VoNR integrates directly with the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) used in VoLTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It uses NAS protocols to establish high-priority QoS flows that support URLLC requirements for voice traffic.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Support for 5G Standalone is a prerequisite for VoNR.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] VoNR benefits from the enhanced security architecture of the 5G Core network, including improved subscriber identity protection.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] VoNR delivers superior audio quality through the Enhanced Voice Services (EVS) codec, which must adhere to rigorous terminal acoustic requirements and standardized testing procedures.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Most phones released since 2023 (such as the iPhone 15 series and newer flagship devices) support VoNR, but availability depends on carrier enablement in specific areas.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 3GPP also defines non-terrestrial networks (NTN) that use satellites and airborne platforms to provide coverage where ground networks are impractical.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G-Advanced, also known as 5.5G or 5G-A, is defined in 3GPP Release 18 as a transition between 5G and 6G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It adds features for more efficient spectrum use, lower energy demand, and higher reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The release introduces AI- and ML-based network management, extended-reality services, and communication support for autonomous systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Release 18 specifies improved time-synchronization methods independent of the GNSS and built-in geolocation functions.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It extends non-terrestrial support to satellite and airborne communication.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G Reduced Capability (RedCap) in 3GPP Release 17 is designed to bridge the gap between high-performance 5G devices and low-power IoT technologies such as LTE-M and NB-IoT.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] It was created to address use cases between Enhanced Mobile Broadband (eMBB), Ultra-Reliable Low-Latency Communications (URLLC), and Massive Machine-Type Communication (mMTC) technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) compiled the first database of 5G-compatible products, listing 23 manufacturers and 33 models across categories such as smartphones, hotspots, and customer-premises equipment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Later surveys recorded more than one hundred announced products from over fifty vendors.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Early 5G modem chipsets were released by Intel, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Samsung, followed by additional platforms in subsequent product generations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The Samsung Galaxy S10 5G was among the first smartphones to support 5G networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Other early 5G models included the Nokia 8.3 5G, designed for operation across low- to mid-band frequencies; the Google Pixel 5 and Pixel 4a (5G); and Apple's iPhone 12 series, the company's first generation with 5G capability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By the early 2020s, most high-end smartphones featured 5G capability, while some consumer devices still lack full support.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] As a result, the practical benefits for mid range phone users have been modest, and 5G adoption has lagged behind expectations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2019, the European Commission and the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) warned that 5G networks could expand potential attack surfaces for state actors, recommending diversification of suppliers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Nokia and Ericsson are the only European manufacturers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Researchers from ETH Zurich and partner universities found weaknesses in the 5G authentication process that could expose users to new security risks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] They concluded that the system was still immature and that its higher data capacity could increase exposure to attacks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] A 2022 study identified a design flaw in the Evolved Packet System (EPS) that could affect device behavior during network switching.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Growth of the Internet of things increases the number of devices connected through 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] IoT Analytics estimated growth from about 7 billion devices in 2018 to over 21 billion by 2025, raising exposure to DDoS attacks, cryptojacking, and other cyberattacks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Concerns about espionage and data access have influenced national policies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom have restricted or banned Chinese-made equipment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] A 2012 report by the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence concluded that equipment from Huawei and ZTE could pose national-security risks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Later assessments by U.S. intelligence agencies warned that Huawei products could allow covert data access.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2022, the FBI reported that Huawei equipment near U.S. military bases could interfere with nuclear communications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Huawei and the Chinese government deny the allegations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Analysts note that China's National Security Law could require companies to provide data to authorities if requested.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2020, the United States Department of State launched The Clean Network initiative to promote data privacy and security among allied nations.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] By year-end, more than 60 countries and 200 telecommunications companies had joined, including most NATO, EU, and OECD members.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Some 5G bands, such as n258 at 26 GHz, are close to frequencies used for passive remote sensing by weather and Earth observation satellites, including water vapor measurements at 23.8 GHz.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Interference with satellite observations could reduce the accuracy of numerical weather prediction models and affect sectors such as commercial aviation.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Navy warned that out-of-band emissions from 5G transmissions near 24 GHz could degrade forecasts by up to 30 %.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The 2019 World Radiocommunication Conference set an interim limit of −33 dBW until 2027, followed by −39 dBW.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) warned that these limits could reduce forecast reliability.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2021–2022, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned that some 5G signals could interfere with aircraft radar altimeters, which operate at 4.2–4.4 GHz, while new 5G services use 3.7–4.0 GHz.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Europe uses lower frequencies (3.4–3.8 GHz), reducing the risk.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Some 5G allocations overlap with frequencies used by C band satellite communication systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Interference can occur when networks operate in 3.3–3.6 GHz, near satellite reception at 3.4–4.2 GHz Mitigation uses low-noise block downconverters and waveguide filters.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] 5G and Wi-Fi 6E share the 6 GHz band, which enables efficient spectrum use but requires coordination to prevent interference.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Both operate under unlicensed conditions in the US and EU, supporting NR-U and Wi-Fi 6E technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Analysts note that marketing of 5G has often overstated its capabilities.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Common concerns include limited user benefits, short range of mmWave signals, and rebranding of non-5G improvements as 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] A 2020 survey by McKinsey & Company found that operators identified few immediately profitable use cases.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Consumer surveys show mixed attitudes, with skepticism about marketing claims and uneven coverage in early deployments.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Industry groups and network operators state that 5G enables faster speeds and lower latency, though results depend on infrastructure rollout and available spectrum.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In contrast to the initial excitement about the prospects, many firms striving for deployment have encountered reality, users are not eager to upgrade the technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Five years after its launch, a majority of users have yet to transition to the new standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Public concern about the effects of wireless signals predates 5G technology.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Similar concerns were raised about earlier mobile standards in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "exposure to intense, direct amounts of non-ionizing radiation may result in tissue damage due to heat.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Some critics argue that existing exposure limits are too lenient or influenced by industry lobbying.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Claims that the use of 5G mobile networks can cause cancer are unsupported by scientific evidence.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Several books making unverified claims about wireless health effects have been published.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] One, by Joseph Mercola, alleged links to ADHD, heart disease, and brain cancer.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Mercola was criticized for promoting misinformation during the COVID-19 pandemic and warned by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for selling unapproved COVID-19 cures.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] According to *The New York Times*, controversy regarding 5G health effects partly originated from an unpublished 2000 report by physicist Bill P.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Curry for the Broward County School Board, which incorrectly concluded that higher-frequency microwaves are absorbed more deeply by the brain.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Later analyses showed that this was a misunderstanding of *in vitro* research results.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Experts noted that millimeter-wave frequencies used by 5G cannot penetrate the skin or reach internal organs.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In a 2019 article, the same newspaper reported that RT America promoted claims linking 5G to diseases such as brain cancer, infertility, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The network aired several such programs in 2019, later cited by numerous blogs and websites.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2019, cities such as Brussels and Geneva temporarily halted 5G rollouts pending radiation assessments.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The Swiss Telecommunications Association stated that studies had not demonstrated adverse health effects from 5G exposure.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Similar debates occurred in the Netherlands, the United States, and the United Kingdom, where some municipalities briefly delayed deployments or issued precautionary statements.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The Food and Drug Administration maintains that existing exposure limits for cellphone radiofrequency energy are sufficient to protect public health.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Low-level electromagnetic fields (EMF) can have measurable biological effects in plants and animals, but research remains inconclusive about health risks to humans.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] A 2019 meta-analysis found that while many *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies detected biological responses to radiofrequency exposure, the evidence did not establish health risks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The rollout of 5G technology began during the COVID-19 pandemic, prompting conspiracy theories that linked 5G to the pandemic.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] These claims led to arson attacks on telecom masts in parts of Europe, including the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and Italy.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In the United Kingdom, at least 61 mobile masts were reportedly set on fire.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] During the early months of the pandemic, Australian anti-lockdown protesters carried anti-5G signs, later connected to broader conspiracy groups.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The second claims that 5G causes COVID-19.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Some versions claim the pandemic hid illnesses blamed on 5G, while others suggest COVID-19 began in Wuhan, one of the first cities with early 5G rollout.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] The marketing of pre-5G technologies refers to the promotion of enhanced 4G networks as precursors or alternatives to 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] Before and during early 5G deployment, some mobile network operators used terms such as "pre-5G", "5G-ready", "4.5G", and "5G Evolution" for upgraded LTE Advanced or LTE Advanced Pro networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] These networks could use features such as carrier aggregation, 256-QAM, and 4×4 MIMO to increase data rates, but they did not use 5G NR, the radio access technology standardized for 5G networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] A notable example was 5G Evolution, introduced by AT&T in 2017 to market higher-speed LTE service.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] AT&T described the service as "a foundation for our evolution to 5G while the 5G standards are being finalized", but technology publications criticized the branding as misleading because the underlying network remained based on LTE technologies rather than 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2019, Sprint sued AT&T, alleging that the 5G Evolution and "5GE" branding misled consumers into believing that they were receiving 5G service.
[src:common-external-power-supply/5g] In 2020, the National Advertising Review Board recommended that AT&T stop using "5G Evolution" and related claims in advertising, finding that the terms were misleading; AT&T said it disagreed with the decision but would comply with the self-regulatory process.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] ITU-R oversees related work by 3GPP and ETSI, together with the Next Generation Mobile Networks (NGMN) Alliance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] 3GPP is finalizing Release 18 for 5G Advanced and preparing Release 19 for early 6G research.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] IMT-2030 defines performance targets for future mobile systems and tracks 6G standardization.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Research and testing are in progress at major equipment vendors, operators, and institutes.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Companies including Ericsson, Nokia, Huawei, Samsung, LG, Apple, NTT Docomo, Airtel, and Jio have announced 6G programs.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Governments in North America, Europe, and Asia are funding national 6G initiatives through the EU, the United States, Russia, China, India, Japan, and South Korea.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] 6G aims to achieve higher data rates, lower latency, and greater energy efficiency than 5G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Planned advances include new air interface designs, improved coding and modulation, and reconfigurable intelligent surfaces.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Research also explores integration with satellite, Wi-Fi, and non-terrestrial networks, as well as distributed edge computing for AR, VR, and AI applications.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Machine learning and AI are expected to help manage networks, allocate spectrum, and optimize services.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] According to the NGMN Alliance, 6G development should focus on demonstrable user needs and avoid unnecessary replacement of existing 5G radio access network equipment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Analysts note that 5G revenue growth has been slower than predicted, leading to a cautious approach to 6G investment.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Commercial deployment of 6G is anticipated in the early 2030s, following standardization milestones later in the 2020s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] 6G networks are expected to be developed and released by the early 2030s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The largest number of 6G patents have been filed in China.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Academic publications since the early 2020s have been conceptualizing 6G and new features that may be included.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The frequency bands for 6G are undetermined.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] One of the challenges in supporting the required high transmission speeds will be the limitation of energy consumption and associated thermal protection in the electronic circuits.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] As of now, mid bands are being considered by WRC for 6G/IMT-2030.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In June 2021, according to Samsung's white paper, using Sub-THz 6G spectrum, their indoor data rate was successful for 6 Gbit/s at 15 meters distance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The following year, Samsung reported 12 Gbit/s at 30 meters distance and 2.3 Gbit/s at 120 meters distance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In September 2023, LG successfully tested 6 Gbit/s transmission and reception at 500 meters distance outdoor.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Research into terahertz radiation (300–3,000 GHz) and millimeter-wave frequencies (30–300 GHz) explores their potential for 6G mobile networks.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] These high frequencies can support large data rates but are easily blocked by obstacles.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Unlike the microwave bands (2–30 GHz) used in 5G and Wi-Fi, and the lower-frequency radio waves used in 1G–4G, their commercial feasibility remains uncertain, as 5G millimeter-wave use is limited by cost.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In 2020, the Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions (ATIS) launched the Next G Alliance, a group including AT&T, Ericsson, Telus, Verizon, T-Mobile, Microsoft, and Samsung.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The alliance aims to advance North American 6G research.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In 2022, researchers from Purple Mountain Laboratories, a state-affiliated institute in Nanjing, China, reported a 206.25 Gbit/s data rate in laboratory tests using the terahertz band.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The team said the results may support future 6G research.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Also in 2022, another Chinese research group reported a data transmission rate of 1 Tbit/s over 1 km using vortex millimeter-wave transmission, a technique that uses radio waves shaped to spiral as they travel.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The work built on earlier European studies from the 1990s.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Vortex waves weaken as they expand with distance.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The researchers used a custom transmitter and receiver to focus and decode multiple rotating wave modes.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In 2023, Nagoya University in Japan created three-dimensional waveguide structures made of superconducting niobium for communication in the 100 GHz range.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The superconducting design reduced signal loss from absorption and radiation and was proposed for high-frequency 6G transmission.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Research on terahertz and millimeter-wave communication continues worldwide as part of global efforts to develop future wireless standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In November 2020, China launched a Long March 6 vehicle that carried a satellite testing components for potential 6G communication.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Chinese state media described it as "the world's first 6G satellite", a claim not independently verified.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The mission studied terahertz-band transmission and other 6G-related technologies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Geopolitical competition during the rollout of 5G has continued to shape the development of 6G.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] During that time, China reduced participation by foreign vendors and relied more on domestic suppliers such as Huawei and ZTE.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Several Western countries later restricted Huawei and ZTE after government investigations accused Chinese firms of cyber-espionage and intellectual-property theft.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] These developments affected early 6G planning and global supply chains.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Analysts have suggested that such divisions could lead to a split in 6G standards.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Analysts also expect competition in international standards bodies to grow.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] A joint statement issued in February 2024 by the United States, Australia, Canada, Czech Republic, Finland, France, Japan, South Korea, Sweden, and the United Kingdom endorsed shared 6G principles for open, global, and secure connectivity.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Governments in several countries, including China and India, have made 6G a national priority.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] The technology appears in China's Fourteenth Five-Year Plan.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] India's 6G direction is defined by the Bharat 6G Vision document, published in 2023.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Governments have also promoted varied technology suppliers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Many support the Open RAN model, which lets hardware and software from different suppliers work together without vendor control.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] Australia's telecommunications strategy includes early 6G planning.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] In March 2025, Telstra announced that 6G is expected in the 2030s, with $800 million set aside to improve existing infrastructure over four years.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] 6G wireless communication networks are envisioned to revolutionize customer services and applications via the IoT (Internet of Things) toward a future of fully intelligent and autonomous systems.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] IoT connects sensor devices and networks to enable communication among people, physical objects, and equipment across a wide range of contexts.
[src:common-external-power-supply/6g] 6G will also use Backscatter Communication for Ambient IoT devices.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The **common external power supply** (**Common EPS**) was a European Commission (EC) specification for a universal charger for smartphones sold within the European Union.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The specification included the use of a USB Micro-B connector and adherence to the USB Battery Charging Specification.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The purpose of the specification was to reduce waste and increase convenience for consumers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Common EPS started as an EC-sponsored agreement between manufacturers, and was formalised into a technical standard by relevant EU standardisation bodies.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The specification EN/IEC 62684 was active from 2009 to 2014.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Although compliance was voluntary, a majority of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers agreed to make their applicable mobile phones compatible.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Apple, one of the major signatories, was still found to be in compliance despite using proprietary connectors for the iPhone, since the specification allowed for the use of adaptors.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] To replace the obsolete specification, the European Union later passed the Radio Equipment Directive (2022), which requires new smartphones to use USB-C by the end of 2024, and laptops by 2026.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In June 2009, many of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers signed an EC-sponsored memorandum of understanding (MoU), agreeing to make most new data-enabled mobile phones marketed in the European Union compatible with a to-be-specified common EPS.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In line with the Dresden agreement signed in 1996 by both CENELEC and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), work was transferred into the IEC.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The original Common EPS memorandum of understanding expired at the end of 2012.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The common EPS specification relies heavily on existing USB electro-mechanical standards – especially the USB Battery Charging Specification.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] By the mid-2000s, many mobile phone manufacturers (as well as manufacturers of other small battery-powered devices) had already begun designing their products with the ability to use a USB port's 5 V DC power to recharge batteries.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The USB Implementers Forum, recognizing this trend, updated the USB standard in 2007 to better accommodate this popular battery-charging application of USB ports, primarily by defining "charging ports" which can provide more current allowing faster re-charging of batteries.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In November 2010, the IEC signed an agreement with the USB Implementers Forum, which led to the IEC incorporating USB specifications into the IEC 62684:2011 International Standard.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] A common EPS must include a cable with a micro USB-B (2.0) connector for connecting to a mobile phone.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] This cable can be either *captive* (permanently attached to the power supply) or detachable.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] If detachable, the cable must connect to the power supply via a standard USB type-A plug.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The MoU which defines the common external power supply as well as the related EC standardisation mandate both allow for the use of the common external power supply also with phones not equipped with a micro-USB receptacle.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] "... [MoU] 4.2.1 ... if a manufacturer makes available an Adaptor from the Micro-USB connector of a Common EPS to a specific non-Micro-USB socket in the Mobile Phone, it shall constitute compliance to this article" and, "...
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The type of AC "plug" provided on a common EPS can vary depending on the intended market of use.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] "Per regulatory requirements for each market. ... preferred supplied input voltage range should be at least 90–264 V" (100–240 V ± 10%).
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Some observers, noting Apple's continued use of proprietary, non-micro USB charging ports on their smartphones, suggested Apple was not in compliance with the 2009 Common EPS Memorandum of Understanding.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In a 2013 amendment to a "Proposal for a Directive of the European Parliament … relating to the making available on the market of radio equipment", the European Committee on the Internal Market and Consumer Protection included a recommendation for "...
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Yet, the draft law (Directive 2014/53/EU), approved overwhelmingly by the European Parliament on 13 March 2014, stipulates that it will be up to the European Commission to decide which specific types of radio equipment will have to be compatible with common chargers.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Once formally approved by the Council of Ministers, member states will have two years to transpose the new regulations into national laws and manufacturers will have an additional year after that to comply.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In January 2020, the European Parliament passed a resolution, calling upon the European Commission to adopt rules on the mandatory introduction of common chargers for all mobile devices.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] In light of the declining popularity of the Micro USB connector and its limited power throughput relative to USB-C, in September 2021, the European Commission adopted a proposal to for a new directive, to update the existing Directive 2014/53/EU.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The directive was approved by the European Parliament and Council of the European Union.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The resulting directive, Radio Equipment Directive 2021/0291 requires all hand-held items sold from 2024 onward to have and be able to charge via a USB Type-C port.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Manufacturers would also be required to offer consumers the option of purchasing their devices without any charging device.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Other mobile phone power supply and charging standards have been implemented in other parts of the world (e.g., Korea and China).
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] Proposals for a global/industry-wide mobile phone charging solution have also been promoted by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) and by industry organizations GSMA and OMTP.
[src:common-external-power-supply/common-external-power-supply] The ITU and the GSMA/OMTP proposals are very similar to the European Common EPS and Chinese charger standards although the GSMA/OMTP proposal is less flexible and has not been adopted by as many phone manufacturers as has the EU standard.
